  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2075894843" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2075894843" />
    <a title="Kevin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35434974-kevin"><img alt="Kevin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607981917p2/35434974.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2075894843?book_show_action=true">Jul 29, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kevin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kevin" href="/user/show/35434974-kevin">Kevin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35434974-kevin?shelf=econ-general">econ-general</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35434974-kevin?shelf=econ-development">econ-development</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2075894843" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18268804630181230508"><b>3rd book I read by Chang, a reformist State Capitalist tearing down Free Market fundamentalism</b>. Given his experiences with South Korea&apos;s rapid development, he is a worthy State Capitalist to engage with.<br/><br/>[2021 update of old reviews]: <br/>--Before we go any further, the most accessible real-world econ 101 book I&apos;ve encountered is still: <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/36490332.Talking_to_My_Daughter_About_the_Economy_or__How_Capitalism_Works___and_How_It_Fails' title='Talking to My Daughter About the Economy or, How Capitalism Works - and How It Fails by Yanis Varoufakis' rel='nofollow noopener'>Talking to My Daughter About the Economy: or, How Capitalism Works - and How It Fails</a>, followed up with solutions in: <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49098225.Another_Now_Dispatches_from_an_Alternative_Present' title='Another Now Dispatches from an Alternative Present by Yanis Varoufakis' rel='nofollow noopener'>Another Now: Dispatches from an Alternative Prese</a></span>
  <span id="freeText18268804630181230508" style="display:none"><b>3rd book I read by Chang, a reformist State Capitalist tearing down Free Market fundamentalism</b>. Given his experiences with South Korea's rapid development, he is a worthy State Capitalist to engage with.<br /><br />[2021 update of old reviews]: <br />--Before we go any further, the most accessible real-world econ 101 book I've encountered is still: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/36490332.Talking_to_My_Daughter_About_the_Economy_or__How_Capitalism_Works___and_How_It_Fails" title="Talking to My Daughter About the Economy or, How Capitalism Works - and How It Fails by Yanis Varoufakis" rel="nofollow noopener">Talking to My Daughter About the Economy: or, How Capitalism Works - and How It Fails</a>, followed up with solutions in: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49098225.Another_Now_Dispatches_from_an_Alternative_Present" title="Another Now Dispatches from an Alternative Present by Yanis Varoufakis" rel="nofollow noopener">Another Now: Dispatches from an Alternative Present</a><br /><br />OK, this book:<br /><br /><b>The Good</b>:<br />--Chang is a “<b>heterodox</b>” economist in that he does not follow mainstream (i.e. Neoclassical) orthodoxies (ex. free market, free trade).<br />--Chang's particular interest is in theories surrounding “<b>Development</b>” economics, which Chang suggests is mostly an array of pragmatic, social (often state) planning throughout history rather than a formalized “school” of economic theory; his methodology is thus rooted in economic history (i.e. the <b>real world</b>) rather than Neoclassical abstractions and convenient <b>thought-experiments</b>. You can get a better sense of this in Chang's history-driven debunking of “free trade” (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1032019.Bad_Samaritans_The_Myth_of_Free_Trade_and_the_Secret_History_of_Capitalism" title="Bad Samaritans The Myth of Free Trade and the Secret History of Capitalism by Ha-Joon Chang" rel="nofollow noopener">Bad Samaritans: The Myth of Free Trade and the Secret History of Capitalism</a>) and his summary of “political economy” (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20613671.Economics_The_User_s_Guide" title="Economics The User's Guide by Ha-Joon Chang" rel="nofollow noopener">Economics: The User's Guide</a>).<br />--Introduces the speed gap between <b>finance</b> (the most liquid to trade) and industry (requires long-term investment), a useful perspective on the Financial sector's tendency to become detached from the real economy and profit from speculative bubbles/rent-seeking. Marxist geographer <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/61592.David_Harvey" title="David Harvey" rel="nofollow noopener">David Harvey</a> has a great video on this (<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtu.be/qOP2V_np2c0">https://youtu.be/qOP2V_np2c0</a>) and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/26855.Michael_Hudson" title="Michael Hudson" rel="nofollow noopener">Michael Hudson</a> is a wizard with Finance capitalism: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/34150000.J_Is_for_Junk_Economics_A_Guide_to_Reality_in_an_Age_of_Deception" title="J Is for Junk Economics A Guide to Reality in an Age of Deception by Michael Hudson" rel="nofollow noopener">J Is for Junk Economics: A Guide to Reality in an Age of Deception</a> and <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PLSQhQoKnYhTXCnmL626Pj0ND7NiCjERMH">https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PLS...</a><br />--Introduces our <b>limited rationality</b> and the dangers of complexity (esp. overly-complex financial instruments)... Interestingly, the frequent reformist buzz-phrase “<b>more transparency</b>” is not an adequate solution here. We do not need more information as we are limited in processing such information; we need to ban such instruments of systemic risk/mass destruction...<br /><br /><b>The Adequate</b>:<br />--Some reviewers criticize the execution for <i>Issue #1: There is no Free Market</i>. I agree, especially because Chang's later book mentions a much more illustrative criticism of Market fundamentalism, when he introduces <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/89879.Herbert_A__Simon" title="Herbert A. Simon" rel="nofollow noopener">Herbert A. Simon</a>. <br />--Simon visualizes the “economy” as being composed of <b>large bodies of complex social relations</b> (i.e. state bureaucracies, corporate hierarchies, other social organizations... and smaller units like families/friends) with some <b>small lines</b> connecting them, some of which symbolize market relations. <br />...Indeed, the capitalist triumph of the <b>corporation</b> itself does not operate using market mechanisms internally, when you enter into it! Work by employees is done in this mass social mobilization by what <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/29101.David_Graeber" title="David Graeber" rel="nofollow noopener">David Graeber</a> (RIP) provocatively calls “baseline communism” (from each according to their ability, to each according to their need), i.e. <b>cooperation</b>/teamwork with all its messy human qualities, all the while propelled (or restrained) by corporate hierarchy. This is not based on market exchange, i.e. sellers/buyers seeking to maximize returns governed by supply/demand, resulting in instant transactions between (in effect) strangers.<br />...“Internal” to a corporation should not be assumed as insignificant, considering the massive centralization of multinational corporations (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38914131.The_People_s_Republic_of_Walmart_How_the_World_s_Biggest_Corporations_are_Laying_the_Foundation_for_Socialism" title="The People’s Republic of Walmart How the World’s Biggest Corporations are Laying the Foundation for Socialism by Leigh Phillips" rel="nofollow noopener">The People’s Republic of Walmart: How the World’s Biggest Corporations are Laying the Foundation for Socialism</a>). Indeed, this is the “<b>socialized production</b>” and “centralization of capital” that Marx saw capitalism forcing (via commodification, wage dependency, and competition between capitalists), growing to contradict capitalist property rights' profit-seeking by the few. <br />--This view is in contrast to the market fundamentalist illustration of an economy of rational self-interested <b>individuals all connected by market exchange</b>, as if the world is simply a collection of individual shopkeepers/Robinson Crusoes, each owning their own means of production and bartering their products to each other (what a convenient thought-experiment for capitalists!). Another useful quote to dispel this myopic thought-experiment (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/19766.Ronald_H__Coase" title="Ronald H. Coase" rel="nofollow noopener">Ronald H. Coase</a>): <blockquote>The time has surely gone in which economists could analyze in great detail two individuals exchanging nuts for berries on the edge of the forest and then feel that their analysis of the process of exchange was complete, illuminating though this analysis may be in certain respects.</blockquote>--Chang's examples of capitalist reforms are interesting, particular his emphasis on prioritizing <b>production</b> (improving technological capacity, physical and social infrastructure) is shared by several other schools of economics outside Neoclassical orthodoxy (i.e. Classical, Marxist, Development, Institutional); still, he seems at his best trashing Free Market fundamentalists in the context of development economics, which his book <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1032019.Bad_Samaritans_The_Myth_of_Free_Trade_and_the_Secret_History_of_Capitalism" title="Bad Samaritans The Myth of Free Trade and the Secret History of Capitalism by Ha-Joon Chang" rel="nofollow noopener">Bad Samaritans: The Myth of Free Trade and the Secret History of Capitalism</a> already focuses on. <br /><br /><b>The Bad</b>:<br />1) Free Market economists are just <b>useful idiots</b>:<br />--Seriously, why play their game? The elites behind “Neoliberalism” know they are engaged in a short-term pillage, a class war (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/183033.A_Brief_History_of_Neoliberalism" title="A Brief History of Neoliberalism by David Harvey" rel="nofollow noopener">A Brief History of Neoliberalism</a>). Elsewhere, Chang acknowledges the methodology of always considering “cui bono?” (“to whom is it a benefit?”), but he is often surprisingly timid with implementing this. <br /><br />2) Capitalism's dynamism is at the same time its <b>volatility towards crises</b>, not to mention such dynamic (and wasteful) growth is not sustainable on a finite planet: <br />-Intro: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/36490332.Talking_to_My_Daughter_About_the_Economy_or__How_Capitalism_Works___and_How_It_Fails" title="Talking to My Daughter About the Economy or, How Capitalism Works - and How It Fails by Yanis Varoufakis" rel="nofollow noopener">Talking to My Daughter About the Economy: or, How Capitalism Works - and How It Fails</a> and case study: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/24886497.And_the_Weak_Suffer_What_They_Must__Europe_s_Crisis_and_America_s_Economic_Future" title="And the Weak Suffer What They Must? Europe's Crisis and America's Economic Future by Yanis Varoufakis" rel="nofollow noopener">And the Weak Suffer What They Must? Europe's Crisis and America's Economic Future</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/108583.The_Corporation_The_Pathological_Pursuit_of_Profit_and_Power" title="The Corporation The Pathological Pursuit of Profit and Power by Joel Bakan" rel="nofollow noopener">The Corporation: The Pathological Pursuit of Profit and Power</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/29885359.Facing_the_Anthropocene_Fossil_Capitalism_and_the_Crisis_of_the_Earth_System" title="Facing the Anthropocene Fossil Capitalism and the Crisis of the Earth System by Ian Angus" rel="nofollow noopener">Facing the Anthropocene: Fossil Capitalism and the Crisis of the Earth System</a><br /><br />3) Return to the “Golden Age of Capitalism” (post-WWII)? Is <b>“Enlightened Capitalism”</b> the end of our social imagination? How golden was post-WWII period, when it required the greatest war in human history as the “<b>creative destruction</b>” to wipe away the stagnant capital of the endless Great Depression and innovate the US's <b>military industrial complex</b>? How “enlightened” was the US aid for rapid industrialization of Japan and South Korea, when these were financed by military contracts from US's genocidal bombings on Korea and Vietnam, respectively? <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42177906.Drums_of_War__Drums_of_Development_The_Formation_of_a_Pacific_Ruling_Class_and_Industrial_Transformation_in_East_and_Southeast_Asia__1945_1980" title="Drums of War, Drums of Development The Formation of a Pacific Ruling Class and Industrial Transformation in East and Southeast Asia, 1945-1980 by Jim Glassman" rel="nofollow noopener">Drums of War, Drums of Development: The Formation of a Pacific Ruling Class and Industrial Transformation in East and Southeast Asia, 1945-1980</a>). And why not mention the many alternatives (from micro to macro) out there? <br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49098225.Another_Now_Dispatches_from_an_Alternative_Present" title="Another Now Dispatches from an Alternative Present by Yanis Varoufakis" rel="nofollow noopener">Another Now: Dispatches from an Alternative Present</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/13591849.Democracy_at_Work_A_Cure_for_Capitalism" title="Democracy at Work A Cure for Capitalism by Richard D. Wolff" rel="nofollow noopener">Democracy at Work: A Cure for Capitalism</a><br />-<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18086269.The_Public_Bank_Solution_From_Austerity_to_Prosperity" title="The Public Bank Solution From Austerity to Prosperity by Ellen Hodgson Brown" rel="nofollow noopener">The Public Bank Solution: From Austerity to Prosperity</a><br /><br />...I review these last 2 issues in reviews of Chang's other books:<br />-<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2075894568?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a><br />-<a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2075936953?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="18268804630181230508" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

