    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_150478648" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/150478648" />
    <a title="Connie Kuntz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1664750-connie-kuntz"><img alt="Connie Kuntz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1614394184p2/1664750.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/150478648?book_show_action=true">Feb 25, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Connie Kuntz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Connie Kuntz" href="/user/show/1664750-connie-kuntz">Connie Kuntz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/10219794-twenty-three-things-they-don-t-tell-you-about-capitalism">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer150478648" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4648967394102626925">This book is a very convincing argument about how utterly bogus the notions of free market and free trade actually are. You can find a quote in every chapter regarding this point. My favorite is found on page 73: <br/><br/>&quot;The free trade, free-market policies that have rarely, if ever, worked. Most of the rich countries did not uses such policies when they were developing countries themselves, while these policies have slowed down growth and increased income inequality in the developing countries in the </span>
  <span id="freeText4648967394102626925" style="display:none">This book is a very convincing argument about how utterly bogus the notions of free market and free trade actually are. You can find a quote in every chapter regarding this point. My favorite is found on page 73: <br /><br />"The free trade, free-market policies that have rarely, if ever, worked. Most of the rich countries did not uses such policies when they were developing countries themselves, while these policies have slowed down growth and increased income inequality in the developing countries in the last three decades. Few countries have become rich through free-trade, free-market policies and few ever will." <br /><br />Ha-Joon Chang wrote 23 chapters ("things") about common misconceptions about U.S. economics. I highly recommend reading this book, but if you are pressed for time, I offer my following synopsis entitled "The Pooping Triangle."<br /><br />Picture a triangle. One point is Immigration. The other point is National Identity. The other point is Government. Immigration needs National Identity to exist so it can exist. National Identity needs the Government to exist so it can exist. Immigration needs the Government to exist so it can exist, and so on... <br /><br />The triangle I am describing is a political triangle that essentially feeds off itself. When the triangle eats too much of itself and has to take a poop, it gives said poop to the poor. The poop is difficult to identify because the triangle gave it a good spin. They spun it very fast. So fast that the poop became so unidentifiable, the poor asked the rich, "What is that?" The rich then answered, "That is the American Dream. That is The Free Market. That is...Your American Duty." <br /><br />If you think that was lame, I offer you the following quote from Donald Rumsfeld found on page 174-175:<br /><br />"There are known knowns. There are things we know that we know. There are known unknowns. That is to say, there are things that we now know we don't know. But there are also unknown unknowns. There are things we do not know we don't know." <br /><br />I stand by my pooping triangle, Mr. Rumsfeld!<br /><br />Moving on, my point is this: it is no secret that the people who run the corporations who are so anti-immigration are the same people who locate their business anywhere (internationally, not just in the U.S.) as long as they profit, in spite of the fact that they are stealing land and opportunity from the natives. It is also no secret that the people who fund the corporations who behave this way are in the government. These superpowers control the majority of the money.<br /><br />And about our money. There is a very funny chapter about the "dead presidents" on our money.<br /><br />age 68:<br />"The dead presidents don't talk. But if they could, they would tell Americans and the rest of the world how the policies that their successors promote today are the exact opposite of what they used in order to transform a second-rate agrarian economy dependent on slave labour into the world's greatest industrial power." <br /><br />And what of those "good old days" anyway? Was there ever such a thing?<br /><br />Before you think I am a total ungrateful jerk, I offer the following paragraph:<br /><br />Do we have opportunity in the United States. Absolutely. Do I love my country? 100%. Am I angry about my life? Not at all. Reading about all of this "big stuff" helps me understand my small life better. <br /><br />While the book considers national identity, ultimately, I am more concerned about my family identity. While the book considers the U.S.'s closest political ally, I find myself thinking about my closest political ally. My husband. While the book also considers Child Labor laws, I find myself thinking about my own childrens' chores. Yes, it is a no-brainer that children shouldn't work by adult standards, but the following quote struck me in a special way.<br /><br />"The same reason why we send our children to school rather than making them compete with adults in the labour market, developing countries need to protect and nurture their producers before they acquire the capabilities to compete in the world market unassisted."<br /><br />When I read that (and other passages about child labour laws) it dawned on me that I need to nurture my kids as kids more, rather than constantly prep them for the adult world. <br /><br />This is a funny, intelligent book. Chang has a way of getting the reader to consider un-patriotic concepts in a humorous, intelligent way. He concludes the book very optimistically and I will defintiely read his other book "Bad Samaritans" in the future. <br /><br />Read this book if you enjoy economics, sociology, current political agendas and raising a family.<br />I recommend that you have your dictionary handy. That is, have it handy unless you can easily and quickly define words such as agrarian, sobriquet, suasion and many others. <br /><br />I also spent a good minute wondering how and when "cotton" became a verb. (I like it as a verb, by the way.)<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4648967394102626925" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

