<div id="review_160803989" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/160803989" />
    <a title="Sarah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1845103-sarah"><img alt="Sarah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1279933200p2/1845103.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/160803989?book_show_action=true">Apr 13, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah" href="/user/show/1845103-sarah">Sarah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer160803989" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2055722783297197365">I consider this a must-read for anyone like me, who does not have an economics background and has become accustomed to the misleading free market rhetoric. It was refreshing to have some of the principles of my own thoughts on the economy reinforced by a prize-winning economist, as well as to hear other more complicated principles developed by Ha-Joon Chang that challenge the current orthodoxy. The book is incredibly straightforward and easy to read, in a conversational voice I would almost call</span>
  <span id="freeText2055722783297197365" style="display:none">I consider this a must-read for anyone like me, who does not have an economics background and has become accustomed to the misleading free market rhetoric. It was refreshing to have some of the principles of my own thoughts on the economy reinforced by a prize-winning economist, as well as to hear other more complicated principles developed by Ha-Joon Chang that challenge the current orthodoxy. The book is incredibly straightforward and easy to read, in a conversational voice I would almost call breezy and fun. No understanding of economics is necessarily, as he explains any concepts that are necessary to understand his points. Chang does not miss an opportunity to point out the hypocrisy and wrongheadedness of certain practices in the supposed free market brand of capitalism, to comic effect. I do plan to read some critiques of his perspective, but this book was well-supported with statistical evidence and did not feel like mere political polemic. </span>
  <a data-text-id="2055722783297197365" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


