<div id="review_1538128191" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1538128191" />
    <a title="Victoriano" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46519541-victoriano"><img alt="Victoriano" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442049979p2/46519541.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1538128191?book_show_action=true">Feb 05, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Victoriano" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Victoriano" href="/user/show/46519541-victoriano">Victoriano</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/46519541-victoriano?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1538128191" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8379987807583760455">If there’s one thing an average 20 year-old steeped in Western culture has heard about, it’s capitalism. It seems to be casually referenced in a lot of films, and television shows, and intellectual conversations in college dorms over your third ramen dinner of the week. Any self-respecting adult knows a thing or two about economics, and Ha-Joon Chang definitely capitalizes (pun intended) on that concept. So, for the people out there who want a cursory glance at the development of capitalism in 3</span>
  <span id="freeText8379987807583760455" style="display:none">If there’s one thing an average 20 year-old steeped in Western culture has heard about, it’s capitalism. It seems to be casually referenced in a lot of films, and television shows, and intellectual conversations in college dorms over your third ramen dinner of the week. Any self-respecting adult knows a thing or two about economics, and Ha-Joon Chang definitely capitalizes (pun intended) on that concept. So, for the people out there who want a cursory glance at the development of capitalism in 300 pages, 23 Things They Don’t Tell You about Capitalism is the book for you.<br /><br />I know that title suggests that something conspiratorial is afoot, but really the entire crux of this book is that capitalist thought permeates through every aspect of society. People just choose to ignore it, and thus passively accepts the concepts of free-market capitalism. To be honest, you will probably realize that you’ve considered most of the ideas in this book at least once in your life, which is sort of the point. What Chang does is give you the vocabulary and the statistics to back up the obvious.<br /><br />This book makes excellent use of the interdisciplinary nature of economics: every one of the 23 points is inextricably linked to politics, anthropology and group psychology. So obviously there’s something in this for you, and your family, and your boss, and that girl in the boho dress you met at a rally once. I also really appreciate the level of restraint that Chang employs when expressing dissenting opinions over free-market capitalism. All he does is lay down some facts, and you get to do the rest. You get to decide what to focus on, and what you want to do with it. And really, isn’t that what capitalism is all about?</span>
  <a data-text-id="8379987807583760455" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


