  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_187498106" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/187498106" />
    <a title="Mat" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5856248-mat"><img alt="Mat" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1408287797p2/5856248.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/187498106?book_show_action=true">Jul 22, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mat" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mat" href="/user/show/5856248-mat">Mat</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781846143281" href="/book/show/9136467-23-things-they-don-t-tell-you-about-capitalism">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer187498106" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer640943698387614304">In this critically-acclaimed book, economic iconoclast Ha-Joon Chang makes a mockery of the beliefs of modern-day capitalists.<br/><br/>Here, in a nutshell, are the 23 points made by the author, who has won the Wassily Leontief Prize for Advancing the Frontiers of Economic Thought.<br/><br/>1. There is no such thing as a free market.<br/><br/>There are always some rules, and they are set by politics, not the market. Wages are set by government through immigration. Child labour and pollution laws were once contested by capita</span>
  <span id="freeText640943698387614304" style="display:none">In this critically-acclaimed book, economic iconoclast Ha-Joon Chang makes a mockery of the beliefs of modern-day capitalists.<br /><br />Here, in a nutshell, are the 23 points made by the author, who has won the Wassily Leontief Prize for Advancing the Frontiers of Economic Thought.<br /><br />1. There is no such thing as a free market.<br /><br />There are always some rules, and they are set by politics, not the market. Wages are set by government through immigration. Child labour and pollution laws were once contested by capitalists, but they are now widely accepted. Free marketeers say they are scientific, but they are political.<br /><br />2. Companies should not be run in the interests of their owners.<br /><br />Shareholders can easily and quickly move their money elsewhere, so they are interested in only short-term profits. Such profits come through cutting overheads such as staff, workers’ rights and pay, none of which benefit companies or economies in the long run.<br /><br />3. Most people in rich countries are paid more than they should be.<br /><br />They are often less skilled than their counterparts in poor countries, but wages are determined by immigration. Free marketeers complain about unions and the minimum wage, but - strangely - not immigration. True free marketeers would let immigrants in.<br /><br />4. The washing machine has changed the world more than the internet has.<br /><br />The washing machine freed up much time and labour, but studies have struggled to find how the internet has changed productivity. Free marketeers fetishise the internet because they say it has brought down international borders, so workers need to be more flexible. Cross-border flows of capital, labour and goods come from politics, not technology.<br /><br />5. Assume the worst about people and you get the worst.<br /><br />Free marketeers believe the market works because everyone is self-seeking. But if that were true, the market would grind to a halt, since everyone would be trying to cheat each other. Companies have to trust their workers - if they spent all their time distrusting and checking staff, their profits would dive.<br /><br />6. Greater macroeconomic stability has not made the world economy more stable.<br /><br />Much has been made of inflation being tamed, but the world economy has become considerably shakier, with a huge number of financial crises and far more job insecurity. Under low inflation, income growth has fallen and the world economy has slowed.<br /><br />7. Free-market policies rarely make poor countries rich.<br /><br />Developing countries grew better under state-led development than free markets. The UK, US and their ilk became rich through protectionism and subsidies, not free markets. In rejecting British pressure to adopt free trade, US president Ulysses Grant said: “Within 200 years, when America has gotten out of protection all that it can offer, it too will adopt free trade.” It has not, yet.<br /><br />8. Capital has a nationality.<br /><br />Much is made of globalisation, but transnational companies remain national companies with international operations. It is hard to move many aspects of a company across borders, including human capital. Firms usually buy only existing firms overseas, rather than creating new ones.<br /><br />9. We do not live in a post-industrial age.<br /><br />As manufacturing productivity has increased, the value of products has decreased in comparison with services. This has led to the false assumption that rich countries now have service economies, since the service sector is worth more. An emphasis on services slows productivity and thus slows economies. It is a fantasy to say developing countries can skip straight to a service economy.<br /><br />10. The US does not have the highest standard of living in the world.<br /><br />US inequality is high, so the average wage is skewed. A dollar in the US can buy more services, but only because labour is cheap due to immigration and low wages. Seven countries had higher per capita income than the US in 2007. Americans also have far less leisure time, so their quality of life is lower and they work more for less pay.<br /><br />11. Africa is not destined for underdevelopment.<br /><br />Africa posted decent growth in the 1960s and 70s. Its so-called physical handicaps such as extreme weather and ethnic divisions are all experienced by rich countries. Free-market policies are the real handicap and policies can be changed.<br /><br />12. Governments can pick winners.<br /><br />South Korea made its steel industry a success against all odds and forced the company LG to go into electronics and Hyundai into shipbuilding. Computers, the internet and biotechnology would not have been developed to the same extent without extensive US government investment. If only businesses knew best, none would make a bad decision, but just look at Microsoft and its disastrous Windows Vista operating system. Saying only the private sector picks winners would ignore half the world’s successes.<br /><br />13. Making rich people richer doesn’t make the rest of us richer.<br /><br />Progressive taxation from 1950 to 1973 brought the highest growth rates in most of the rich capitalist countries, known as “The Golden Age of Capitalism“. With tax cuts for the rich, investment as a rate of national output has fallen. The best way out of a downturn is to give money to the poor, because they spend it.<br /><br />14. US managers are over-priced.<br /><br />They are paid 10 times more than their more successful predecessors in the 1960s and 20 times more than their more successful contemporaries in other countries. To justify their pay, they must increase short-term profits by damaging their companies’ long-term prospects, eventually requiring taxpayer-funded bailouts. Therefore, CEO pay should not be determined by the market.<br /><br />15. People in poor countries are more entrepreneurial than people in rich countries.<br /><br />They have to be to survive. In rich countries, most people work for companies. In poor countries, half or more of the non-agricultural workforce is self-employed - 87.7% in Benin, but only 7.5% in the US. Poor countries have individual entrepreneurs, but rich countries get rich through collective entrepreneurship, supported by infrastructure, legislation, education and co-operation between companies.<br /><br />16. We are not smart enough to leave things to the market.<br /><br />Even Nobel prize-winning economists and top bankers do not truly understand complex financial instruments. Instruments that are too complex for experts to understand should be banned, like dangerous products.<br /><br />17. More education in itself is not going to make a country richer.<br /><br />The east Asian “miracle economies” had lower literacy rates than less successful economies. From 1980 to 2004, literacy rates in sub-Saharan Africa rose, but per capita income fell. Karl Marx said capitalists deliberately de-skill the workforce to make them more sackable and to increase production through mechanisation.<br /><br />18. What is good for General Motors is not necessarily good for the United States.<br /><br />It is best to restrict the freedom of firms so they do not destroy human and natural resources. Instead of making better cars, GM called for protectionism and turned itself into a finance company, eventually requiring a $US57 billion bailout.<br /><br />19. Despite the fall of communism, we are still living in planned economies.<br /><br />Capitalist governments pay for a significant share of research and development, infrastructure, and plan a large chunk of the economy through state-owned enterprises. Capitalists expect CEOs to have detailed business plans, so they should not expect governments to be dictated to by the whims of the market.<br /><br />20. Equality of opportunity may not be fair.<br /><br />Even if, say, education is open to all, some children will still be disadvantaged through malnutrition. It’s like a race where everyone has a head start but some people run with weights on their legs. Equality of outcome can only be achieved through a welfare state.<br /><br />21. Big government makes people more open to change.<br /><br />If people have welfare and retraining to fall back on, they will be more open to change in their work, making for a more dynamic economy.<br /><br />22. Financial markets need to become less, not more, efficient.<br /><br />Holders of financial assets can move their money around too quickly, leading to economic instability. The move to financial assets means long-term investments have declined, leading to slower growth.<br /><br />23. Good economic policy does not require good economists.<br /><br />The most successful economic bureaucrats are usually not economists - they were lawyers in Japan and Korea and engineers in Taiwan and China. Economists are harmful for economies and people. Their influence culminated in the 2008 financial crisis. We have far more to learn from the likes of Marx than from free-market economists.</span>
  <a data-text-id="640943698387614304" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


