  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2361378163" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2361378163" />
    <a title="Mark" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/18948094-mark"><img alt="Mark" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1487208877p2/18948094.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2361378163?book_show_action=true">May 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mark" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mark" href="/user/show/18948094-mark">Mark</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141047973" href="/book/show/10733801-23-things-they-don-t-tell-you-about-capitalism">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2361378163" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9044327277652442427">Matt Ridley and Ha-Joon Chang are locked in a room and told to fight to the death. Who wins?<br/><br/>Anyway, in &apos;23 Things They Don&apos;t Tell You About Capitalism&apos;, economist Ha-Joon Chang concludes 23 Things with a simple &quot;it is time to get uncomfortable&quot;. Aiming to make fervent neo-liberals feel just that, in 23 Things Chang eviscerates neo-liberalism for being woefully inefficient at producing beneficial long-term substantive growth. <br/><br/>23 Things is written in a very accessible manner, with Chang not gettin</span>
  <span id="freeText9044327277652442427" style="display:none">Matt Ridley and Ha-Joon Chang are locked in a room and told to fight to the death. Who wins?<br /><br />Anyway, in '23 Things They Don't Tell You About Capitalism', economist Ha-Joon Chang concludes 23 Things with a simple "it is time to get uncomfortable". Aiming to make fervent neo-liberals feel just that, in 23 Things Chang eviscerates neo-liberalism for being woefully inefficient at producing beneficial long-term substantive growth. <br /><br />23 Things is written in a very accessible manner, with Chang not getting excessively technical except where absolutely necessary and even then, you don't need have a postgraduate qualification in economics to follow his arguments. In fact, Chang firmly believes that most, if not all, economic principles can be explained in a relatively simple way once most of the language is simplified. <br /><br />Pointing a razor-sharp sword towards shareholder value maximisation, increased deregulation, excessive CEO pay and the apparently self-serving managerial class as being a direct cause of our economic myopia, Chang refreshingly establishes with compelling evidence why our current economic model is broken and doomed to endless cycles of boom and bust, unfairness and stagnancy.<br /><br />Rather interestingly, Chang makes quite a few seemingly counter-intuitive claims about the economy, including, but not limited to: the impact of the internet on productivity is highly exaggerated; education is not integral to a nation's economic growth; and that we ought to stop viewing ourselves rational beings, particularly in finance. These aren't statements I necessarily agree with, but Chang argues very well for these points and does present some interesting things to consider.<br /><br />If there are any downsides to the book, parts of the arguments from the free-market perspective can come off as straw men, and at times some of the arguments concerning labour practices do not feel as well fleshed out as they could have been. But of particular note, and clearly an incredibly compelling part of his argument, are his summaries of the economic histories of developing and wealthy countries. Using history as his guide, Chang masterfully argues for the need for developing countries to adopt protectionist policies to guard their infant industries.<br /><br />Overall it's a solid piece of work, and whilst not perfect, it's certainly compelling reading that deserves its place on the shelf of good pop-economics/politics books. <br /><br />Now, about that Matt Ridley fight...</span>
  <a data-text-id="9044327277652442427" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


